description: Performance and health metrics for your DotNet Web Servers using Telegraf and Prometheus

panels.description:
Displays the number of exceptions thrown per second.

This includes both .NET exceptions and unmanaged exceptions that are converted into .NET exceptions.
panels.title: Exceps/Sec

panels.description:
An unhandled error is any run-time exception that is not trapped in user code and enters the ASP.NET internal error-handling logic.

This counter is reset with each recycle.
panels.title: Unhandled Errors

panels.description:
The total number of errors that occur during the execution of HTTP requests, including any parser, compilation, or run-time errors.

This counter is reset with each recycle.
panels.title: Errors Total

panels.description: Status code 200
panels.title: Requests Succeeded

panels.description:
Any status codes greater than or equal to 400.

Includes Requests Not Found and Requests Timed Out.
panels.title: Req. Failed

panels.description: This value is calculated over the base line of (No of Logical CPUS * 100)
panels.title: CPU Usage

panels.description: Working Set refers to the total physical memory (RAM) used by the process. However, unlike private bytes, this also includes memory-mapped files and various other resources.
panels.title: Working Set

panels.description: Private Bytes refer to the amount of memory that the process executable has asked for - not necessarily the amount it is actually using. They are "private" because they (usually) exclude memory-mapped files (i.e. shared DLLs).
panels.title: Private Bytes

panels.description: 1 - Uninitialized, 2 - Initialized, 3 - Running, 4 - Disabling, 5 - Disabled, 6 - Shutdown Pending, 7 - Delete Pending
panels.title: Application Pool State

panels.description: The number of times that the application pool has been recycled since Windows Process Activation Service (WAS) started.
panels.title: Recycles

panels.description: The length of time that the application pool has been running since Windows Process Activation Service (WAS) started.
panels.title: Uptime

panels.description: The number of times that worker processes have crashed since the application pool was started.
panels.title: Worker Process Failures

panels.description:
The number of active request pipeline instances for the specified ASP.NET application.

Since only one execution thread can run within a pipeline instance, this number gives the maximum number of concurrent requests that are being processed for a given application.
panels.title: Pipeline Instance Count

panels.description: The number of milliseconds the most recent request was waiting in the queue.
panels.title: Request Wait Time

panels.description: Status code 500
panels.title: Requests Timed Out

panels.description: Status code 404 or 414
panels.title: Requests Not Found

panels.description: The total number of requests since the service was started.
panels.title: Requests Total

panels.description:
The total number of compilations that have taken place during the lifetime of the current Web server process.

Compilation occurs when a file with an .aspx, .asmx, .ascx, or .ashx file name extension, or a code-behind source file, is dynamically compiled on the server.
panels.title: Compilations Total

panels.description:
The total number of unhandled errors that occur during the execution of HTTP requests.

An unhandled error is any run-time exception that is not trapped in user code and enters the ASP.NET internal error-handling logic.
panels.title: Unhandled Errors During Execution

panels.description:
The total number of errors that occur during the execution of HTTP requests, including any parser, compilation, or run-time errors.

This counter is the sum of the Errors During Compilation, Errors During Preprocessing, and Errors During Execution counters.
panels.title: Errors Total

panels.description:
Displays the number of exceptions thrown per second.

This includes both .NET exceptions and unmanaged exceptions that are converted into .NET exceptions. For example, an HRESULT returned from unmanaged code is converted to an exception in managed code.

This counter includes both handled and unhandled exceptions. It is not an average over time; it displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval. This counter is an indicator of potential performance problems if a large (>100s) number of exceptions are thrown.
panels.title: # of Exceptions Thrown/Sec

panels.description:
Displays the percentage of elapsed time spent in JIT compilation since the last JIT compilation phase.

This counter is updated at the end of every JIT compilation phase. A JIT compilation phase occurs when a method and its dependencies are compiled.
panels.title: % Time In JIT

panels.description:
Displays the total number of threads that are currently waiting to acquire a managed lock in the application.

This counter is not an average over time; it displays the last observed value.
panels.title: Current Queue Length

panels.description:
Displays the number of threads per second that are waiting to acquire a lock in the application.

This counter is not an average over time; it displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval.
panels.title: Queue Length/Sec

panels.description: Displays the total number of times that threads in the runtime have attempted to acquire a managed lock unsuccessfully.
panels.title: Total # of Contentions

panels.description:
Displays the number of current managed thread objects in the application.

This counter maintains the count of both running and stopped threads. This counter is not an average over time; it displays only the last observed value.
panels.title: # of current logical Threads

panels.description: Displays the number of native operating system threads created and owned by the common language runtime to act as underlying threads for managed thread objects.
panels.title: # of current physical Threads

panels.description:
Displays the percentage of elapsed time that was spent performing a garbage collection since the last garbage collection cycle.

This counter usually indicates the work done by the garbage collector to collect and compact memory on behalf of the application. This counter is updated only at the end of every garbage collection. This counter is not an average; its value reflects the last observed value.
panels.title: % Time in GC

panels.description:
Displays the sum of the Gen 1 Heap Size, Gen 2 Heap Size, and Large Object Heap Size counters.

This counter indicates the current memory allocated in bytes on the garbage collection heaps.
panels.title: # Bytes in all Heaps

panels.description:
Displays the number of bytes per second allocated on the garbage collection heap.

This counter is updated at the end of every garbage collection, not at each allocation. This counter is not an average over time; it displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples divided by the duration of the sample interval.
panels.title: Allocated Bytes/Sec

panels.description:
Displays the number of garbage-collected objects that survive a collection because they are waiting to be finalized.

If these objects hold references to other objects, those objects also survive but are not counted by this counter.
panels.title: Finalization Survivors

panels.description:
Displays the number of pinned objects encountered in the last garbage collection.

A pinned object is one that the garbage collector cannot move in memory.
panels.title: # of Pinned Objects

panels.description: Displays the percentage of elapsed time spent performing runtime code access security checks since the last sample.
panels.title: % Time in RT checks

panels.description:
Displays the depth of the stack during that last runtime code access security check.

Runtime code access security checks are performed by walking the stack. This counter is not an average; it displays only the last observed value.
panels.title: Stack Walk Depth

panels.description:
Displays the total number of runtime code access security checks performed since the application started.

Runtime code access security checks are performed when a caller demands a particular permission. The runtime check is made on every call by the caller and examines the current thread stack of the caller. When used with the Stack Walk Depth counter, this counter indicates the performance penalty that occurs for security checks.
panels.title: Total Runtime Checks
